column12: IMPLANTIERBARE MEDIZINISCHE AKTIVE VORRICHTUNG MIT BEWERTUNG DES INTRAKARDIALEN VOLUMEN
column13: The system has a circuit to measure an intracardial bioimpedance, with a generator (22) and an amplifier (24) for injection of current and collection of a differential potential at respective poles of connection terminals. Intracardial volume is evaluated using linear or hyperbolic conversion by receiving a dynamic impedance signal to output a dynamic value of volume, representing an absolute instantaneous value of the volume. The connection terminals are connected to an atrial electrode (16), proximal ventrical electrode (18) and a distal ventrical electrode (20) placed in at least three respective distinct sites of myocardium (14).
column15: COOPER DANIEL

column12: Dual sensor rate responsive pacemaker
column13: An electronic pacemaker generating pacing signals includes both a metabolic rate responsive sensor monitoring a physiological parameter and an activity rate responsive sensor monitoring movement of a patient's body during exercise. The measurements from each of the sensors are used to develop a corresponding rate signal and the two signals are combined to generate a dual sensor rate used to determine the timing of the pacing signals. The physiological parameter may be for example minute volume variation while the body movement may be monitored for example by using an accelerometer. The activity rate responsive sensor output is preferably used as an indication of a transition of a level of exercise, when a faster change in the pacing rate is desirable.
column15: COOPER DANIEL

column13: An elongate member 100 for aligning building elements 200 comprises markings corresponding to a dimension of the building elements, wherein the elongate member is elastic. A method of building comprising aligning a plurality of building elements in a row 200 using an elongate member comprising markings 102 is also described. column12: Move Mobile - An assistive device for falls
column13: Abstract: Move Mobile - An Assistive Device for Falls This device is an automated machine that will enable you to stand up following a fall. Utilizing pneumatic pressure and GPS tracking, you will be able to stand back up no matter where you are in the house. The device allows you to live independently for longer, avoid the fear of being stuck following a fall and restore your confidence with your day-to-day tasks. column12: Implantable medical active system with evaluating of intracardiale volume
column13: Ce dispositif comprend une pluralité de bornes reliées à des électrodes placées en au moins trois sites respectifs distincts du myocarde, et des moyens de mesure d'une bioimpédance intracardiaque par injection d'un courant et recueil d'un potentiel différentiel à des pôles respectifs d'une configuration de ces bornes, pour délivrer en sortie un signal dynamique d'impédance fonction du courant injecté et du potentiel différentiel correspondant recueilli. Il comprend en outre des moyens évaluateurs de volume intracardiaque, recevant en entrée le signal d'impédance (Z) et délivrant en sortie une valeur dynamique de volume (Vol) représentative de la valeur absolue instantanée d'un volume intracardiaque. Les moyens évaluateurs opèrent la conversion de l'impédance en volume selon un caractéristique linéaire de la forme Vol =  a .Z +  b  ou, de préférence, hyperbolique de la forme Vol =  a /(Z +  b ).
column15: COOPER DANIEL

column12: EXTRUSION OF METAL MATERIAL USING A DUMMY BLOCK HAVING A CURVED SURFACE
column13: Various embodiments provide for an extrusion device with a dummy block having a curved surface configured to change the shape and length of charge welds between extrudates originating from different billets in order to reduce the amount of scrap and waste material. In an embodiment, the dummy block, which forces the billet of material through the die, can have a concave front surface such that the material, as it is extruded through the die, forms a solid-state weld that is shorter than a flat faced dummy block. In another embodiment, the dummy block can have a convex front surface such that the material, as it is extruded through the die, forms a solid-state weld that is longer than a weld due to a flat faced dummy block. In other embodiments, billets with non-flat ends can also be used.
column15: COOPER DANIEL ROSS

column12: Improvements in or relating to a delayed-release locking device
column13: 948,100. Time-delayed fastenings. G. Q. PARACHUTE CO. Ltd. April 27, 1962 [May 4, 1961], No. 16248/61. Heading E2A. A delayed release locking device comprises means at one end for attaching a load, means at the other end for attaching a supporting means for the load, locking means for holding an attachment, and a timing mechanism which is held immobilised until a predetermined strain developed between the two ends of the device trips the timing mechanism which after a delay has expired, releases the locking means to release the attachment. As shown, the device comprises a first housing 1 mounted for axial movement within a second housing 7. The first housing includes a part 2 carrying a swivel eye 3, a part 4 and an annular toothed union 5 securing the parts 2 and 4 together. The union 5 consists of a ring having a plurality of lugs 6 projecting coaxially therefrom. The housing 7 is formed by an annular sleeve 8 and a head 9 in which are pivoted, on a shaft 9, a pair of spring-loaded detent lugs 12, 13. The sleeve 8 is provided with apertures 18 complementary to the lugs 6. A rigging line ring 19 is secured in position on the head 9 by portions 20 of a sleeve 21 which is screwed on to the head. The lugs 12, 13 each extend through a square hole in a cap 24 closing a timing mechanism compartment, each lug being provided with a cut-away portion 25, which together constitute a square hole into which a square spigot 26 can be caused to extend. The spigot 26 is carried by a threaded shaft 28 which is driven from a spring loaded clockwork mechanism. A spring-loaded U- shaped element 39 extends through the cap 24 and a plate 38, the cross piece of the element 39 carrying an arm 44 which is engageable with one of four projections 45 provided on a gearwheel 36 of the mechanism. The swivel eye 3 includes a ball race 49 and an externally screwed and flanged tubular member 50. A key 52 extends through the member 50, the key having two parallel limbs 53, a guide slot 54 for a screw 55 and a screwed outer end 56, which is engaged by a nut 59. A nut 57 is engaged on the member 50 and the nut 57, swivel 3 and member 50 are locked together by a screw 58. A pin 60 extends through the member 50. In operation, for releasing loop tapes 64 of a drogue sock 63 which encloses a stabilizer parachute 62 the drag exerted on a person to which the device is attached causes movement between the housings 1 and 7 to depress the element 39 and thus free the gearwheel 36 to allow the clockwork mechanism to unwind, the spigot 26 to withdraw from the lugs 12, 13, which then move radially inwardly to disengage the cap 24 and free the housings 1 and 7 for relative axial movement so that the lugs 6 become clear of the tops of the apertures 18 whereby to free the tapes 64 and permit operation of the parachute 62. The device is reset to the condition shown in Fig. 1 by attaching the parachute and drogue sock, rotating screw 55 to withdraw its free end from the key 52, rotating the nut 59 to move the key 52 towards the clockwork mechanism until limbs 53 of the key are disposed on each side of a pin 48 and the pin 60. The mechanism can then be rewound by rotating the swivel eye 3 and nut 57 and moving the mechanism axially to depress the element 39. Continued rotation of the eye 3 rotates nut 29 to re-engage the spigot 26 with the lugs 12, 13 and the key is retracted by rotating nut 59.
column15: COOPER DANIEL WAUMSLEY

column13: 1,022,078. Releasable fastenings. G. Q. PARACHUTE CO., Ltd. July 14, 1964 [Aug. 6, 1963], No. 30954/63. Heading E2A. A quick release device for holding a number of lugs, for example, lugs attached to a harness for a parachutist comprises a body 18, a control member 11 mounted on the body for rotary and axial movement thereto and a plate 20 integrally formed with spigots 22 on which the lugs are held, the lugs being retained on the spigots by spring-pressed members 24 carried by the body, the lugs being released from the spigots by movement of the plate away from the lugs. In the construction shown the body is screwed to a back plate 12 which also has a slot to receive a harness strap and the body is surrounded by a base ring 13 which is also attached to the plate 12. The control member 11 which forms a cover for the body carries a screw 16 which mates with a threaded bore in the spigot plate 20 so that the control member can be rotated relative to the spigot plate 20. The spigot plate has four spigots 22 which are chamfered towards the outer edges to assist in the insertion of the harness lugs. Holes 40 are provided in the spigot plate to accommodate pillars 39 which are screwed into the back plate 12 and the pillars prevent rotation of the spigot plate and also prevent the lugs being held by the spigots 22 during the release operation. The spigot plate is retained in the body by plungers 17 which are loaded by springs 27. The body contains two plungers 21 which are pressed by springs 19 towards the control member 11 and each of which has balls 41 at their outer ends to reduce friction as the control member is rotated and which enter depressions to limit rotation of the control member. The members 24 are hinged in the body about hinge pins 25 and are pressed towards the spigot plate 20 by springs 24. The control member has a central spigot 42 which carries a cam 33 and a pin 34, and a spring 26 presses the cam 33 against the pin 34. The cam has two side tongues which ride in slots in a portion not shown which projects from the back plate; the coaction of the pin and the cam prevents accidental movement of the control member 11. The back plate also carries stops 37 which slide in a well 45 and are held apart by a spring 28. These stops carry L-shaped projections 46, the upper faces of which normally lie under the spigot plate 20 to prevent its depression; rotation of the control member 11 from its normal position however through 90 degrees causes the lower part of the screw 16 to engage cam surfaces on the stops 37 to press the stops together sufficiently to allow the spigot plate to be pressed down over the projections 46; this lowers the spigot plate relative to the members 24 and produces gaps through which the harness lugs can be withdrawn. During the downward movement of the spigot plate the top surfaces of the pillars 39 engage the harness lugs and holds the lugs so that the downward movement of the plate disengages the spigots from-the lugs. The lugs can only be engaged with the spigots when the control member is in its normal non-rotated position and this is accomplished by pivoting the members 24 against the bias of their springs. In any other position of the control member movement of the members 24 is prevented by their engagement with the plungers 21 which have an upward movement as the control member is turned. The construction shown has four spigots each of which accommodates one lug but in a modification there are three spigots one of which can accommodate two lugs; in this case the recess around the spigot in the plate 20 is deeper and the pillar 39 is provided with a spring loaded portion to assist the release of the lugs. The control member is provided with four thumb depressions which form a grip for turning the member and the disposition of which indicates to the wearer whether the control member is in the normal "locking" position or in the position 90 degrees rotated from this position, i.e. the "releasing" position. A visual indicator can also be fitted in the side of the control member which shows one colour at the top of the control member for one position of rotation and another colour for the other position.

column12: Refrigerant compositions.
column13: A composition useful as a refrigerant comprising a mixture of bromotrifluoromethane (R-13B1) and 1,1-di- floroethane (R-152a). The fig. illustrates the use of the said composition. A compressor (1) compresses the gaseous refrigerant mixture into a condenser (2) where the refrigerant mixture liquifies giving off heat which is distributed to the inside of a house by means of a fan (3). Liquid refrigerant mixture leaving condenser (2) is throttled through an expansion device (4). In an evaporator (5), refrigerant mixture evaporates, taking up heat from the air being blown over the evaporator (5) by a fan (6). A part of the refrigerant mixture will remain liquid at low outside temperatures and will collect in a reservoir (7). The device employs aJ-shaped exit tube (8) having a capillary opening (9) at its lowest point for returning liquid refrigerant and oil to the circuit.

column12: Soft tissue fixation device
column13: Method and apparatus are described for a soft tissue fixation device for being biased between a soft tissue graft and an interference screw in a bone tunnel. The device has a contoured body portion having an inner surface and an outer surface. A plurality of spikes protrude from the outer surface of the body portion, the spikes extending perpendicular to the longitudinal axis of the body portion and parallel to each other. The distal ends of the spikes define a flat plane. A pin axially extends from the body portion for receiving a portion of the graft.

column12: OFDR SYSTEM FOR LOCALIZED VIBRATION DETECTION
column13: A vibration detector and method of measuring vibration are described. The vibration detector includes an optical fiber comprising a reference reflector and a delay coil, and one or more sensors comprised at respective one or more locations in the optical fiber, each of the one or more sensors including a center reflector and two side reflectors on either side of the center reflector, the delay coil eliminating detection of interference among reflections from the one or more sensors. The vibration detector also includes a light source to introduce light into the optical fiber to interrogate the optical fiber, a detector to obtain interference signals, each of the interference signals being based on interference between reflections from the reference reflector and one of the one or more sensors; and a processor to process each of the interference signals to obtain vibration measurements.
column15: COOPER DANIEL BOYD

column12: Improvements in or relating to buckles
column13: 1,040,428. Buckles. G. Q. PARACHUTE CO. Ltd. Jan. 14, 1965 [Feb. 27, 1964], No. 8154/64. Headings E2A and E2B. A buckle comprises a slidable bar 16 engageable with a strap end portion, a member against which the strap end portion is held by the bar 16, means which exert pressure on the strap end portion against the bar, which pressure can be relaxed to allow the strap end portion to be adjusted, and means by which the said member can be moved away from the bar to release the strap end portion. As described the buckle comprises two bars 16 having end portions 18 slidable in slots 14, and the corresponding members are bars 17 carried by connecting plates 22 and slidable in slots 15. In use the strap end portions are passed round the bars 16 and are held by pressure plates 38 urged outwardly by pins 37 which engage cam surfaces 34 of an operating plunger connected to a knob (not shown). Tension on the strap end portions moves the bars 16 towards the bars 17 to further grip the portions. To release the strap end portions the knob is rotated to relax the pressure exerted by the plates 38, and then the knob is depressed so that rods connected thereto act via pins 26, 23 and crank 24 to move the connecting plates 22 and hence move the bars 17 away from the bars 16 to release pressure on the strap end portions and allow them to be freed.

column12: Foldable guitar stand
column13: A foldable guitar stand includes: two main support legs; two vertical support members; two rear legs; and a brace. With respect to each side of the guitar stand, one main support leg, one vertical support member, and one rear leg pivot relative to each other about a common axis defined by a pin. The first vertical support member is then operably joined to the second vertical support member by a hinge, and the brace extends between and further connects the vertical support members. In a deployed position, each of the main support legs is rotated about the respective axes defined by the pins to a position in which a substantially flat foot portion of the main support legs can engage the underlying ground surface. Each of the rear legs is rotated away from the respective main support legs to a position in which the respective foot portions can engage the underlying ground surface. The two vertical support members (which are hinged together) are then rotated into an upright orientation.

column12: DISTRIBUTED OPTICAL SENSORS FOR ACOUSTIC AND VIBRATION MONITORING
column13: An apparatus for sensing vibration in a borehole penetrating the earth includes an optical fiber having a plurality of pairs of reflectors configured to reflect light between each of the pairs of reflectors in the plurality, wherein each pair of reflectors is separated by a nominal distance L and an adjacent pair of reflectors in the plurality are separated by a nominal distance D, and an optical interrogator configured to sense a distance between each pair of reflectors in the plurality over time to sense the vibration. A laser emits semi-coherent light over a swept range of wavelengths to illuminate the optical fiber, wherein the semi-coherent light provides for sensing over distance L in the optical fiber between each pair of reflectors and for no sensing in the optical fiber over distance D between different pairs of reflectors. A photodetector senses light received from the optical fiber.

column12: EXTRUSION OF METAL MATERIAL USING A DUMMY BLOCK HAVING A CURVED SURFACE
column13: Various embodiments provide for an extrusion device with a dummy block having a curved surface configured to change the shape and length of charge welds between extrudates originating from different billets in order to reduce the amount of scrap and waste material. In an embodiment, the dummy block, which forces the billet of material through the die, can have a concave front surface such that the material, as it is extruded through the die, forms a solid-state weld that is shorter than a flat faced dummy block. In another embodiment, the dummy block can have a convex front surface such that the material, as it is extruded through the die, forms a solid-state weld that is longer than a weld due to a flat faced dummy block. In other embodiments, billets with non-flat ends can also be used.
column15: COOPER DANIEL ROSS

Ironing - machines with pressing action only.-Relates to a device for carrying the work-support and to the pressure-producing, mechanism. Co-operating with a fixed head 5 are work-supports 9 slidably mounted upon a rotary carrier 6 by means of stems 8 fitting into sockets 7. Rotation of the heads 9 is prevented by parallel guide-bars 11 engaging sockets 12, springs 13 being provided to prevent jamming. Pressure is applied to each stem 8 by means of toggle links 14, 15 operated by a hand-lever 21 through a link 23. The upper link 14 is attached to a pivoted link 17, which carries an adjustable wedge piece 19 for varying the length of the toggle. A lever 25 mounted upon a shaft 26 furnished with a foot-lever 28 is jointed to the lever 15 forming a toggle 27 therewith. In operation, an article having been placed upon the work support 9, the carrier 6 is rotated to bring the support into alinement with the head 5, in which position it is locked by means of a spring bolt 35 engaging in a recess in the carrier. The hand-lever 21 is then operated to apply a preliminary pressure, and is locked by means of a spring dog 47 engaging with a notched quadrant 50, after which the foot lever 28 is depressed and, by straightening the toggle 27, imparts a final pressure. By depressing a treadle 33, the treadle 28 is raised to break the toggle 27, after which the lever 21 may be operated to break the toggle 14, 15. Further depression of the treadle 33 withdraws the bolt 35 through the medium of a link 44, lever 43, shaft 42, and lever 41, releasing the carrier 6.

column12: DISTRIBUTED OPTICAL SENSORS FOR ACOUSTIC AND VIBRATION MONITORING
column13: An apparatus for sensing vibration in a borehole penetrating the earth includes an optical fiber having a plurality of pairs of reflectors configured to reflect light between each of the pairs of reflectors in the plurality, wherein each pair of reflectors is separated by a nominal distance L and an adjacent pair of reflectors in the plurality are separated by a nominal distance D, and an optical interrogator configured to sense a distance between each pair of reflectors in the plurality over time to sense the vibration. A laser emits semicoherent light over a swept range of wavelengths to illuminate the optical fiber, wherein the semi-coherent light provides for sensing over distance L in the optical fiber between each pair of reflectors and for no sensing in the optical fiber over distance D between different pairs of reflectors. A photodetector senses light received from the optical fiber.

column12: Quick-release device for parachute and similar safety harnesses
column13: 914,353. Latch fastenings. G.Q. PARACHUTE CO. Ltd. Feb. 27, 1961 [March 9, 1960], No. 8286/60. Class 44. A quick-release device for parachute or similar safety harness includes a control member 10 operatively connected to a plurality of spring-loaded plungers 88, part of the control member being housed within a box or casing 10, each of the spring-loaded plungers being engageable with a hole in a lug on the end of one of the harness straps and the arrangement being such that when the lugs are pushed into the box or casing, they cause the plungers to move axially by overriding their bevelled ends, the plungers returning by spring force to their original position to engage the holes in the lugs which are thus retained in position and when one or more of the lugs is so engaged disengagement of the plunger or plungers from the lug or lugs is achieved by rotating the control member relatively to the box or casing from a loading position on which its axial movement is prevented, to a discharge position in which such axial movement may take place, in which discharge position it may be moved axially to a release position, its operative connection with the spring-loaded plungers being such that this axial movement causes axial movement of the spring-loaded plungers so that the harness lugs are released, self-locking safety means being provided for locking the plungers to positively prevent axial movement thereof relative to the control member after the harness lugs have been loaded and which ensure that the lugs can only be loaded when the control member is in the loading position in which axial movement relative to the box or casing is prevented. As shown, a sleeve 80 surrounds each of the plungers, a catch 94 carried by each of the plungers and forming one of the safety locking means being engageable with the sleeve and each being engaged by a spider 52 which is connected to the control member 60. Each of the plungers is biased by a spring 156 and this spring also engages the catch 94 to urge it into engagement with the sleeve. The spider 52 has four arms, each of which is formed with bifurcated ends and these engage slots in the sleeves 80 so that when the spider is moved axially the sleeves must also move. The plungers are each provided with cut-away portions in register with the slots so that the plungers can move independently of the sleeves. The control member 60 is connected to the spider so that it can rotate with respect to the spider but so that it moves the spider when it is moved axially. The control member is rigidly connected to a cover 142 by which it is operated and it has a cavity 70 formed within it which consists of two series of conjoined cam faces which are arranged horizontally and the ends of which are connected together by verticallydisposed channels each of which has a step. A cam follower 74, not shown, is disposed horizontally in the box or casing and is urged by a spring into the cavity to engage the cam faces. Also mounted in the box or casing is a locking device 104 constituting another of the safety means which can lock the control member against rotation by engaging a notch 64 in a flange 58. The locking device is biased by a spring 110. A spring-loaded plunger 128 is provided in the body which co-operates with a lug 148 on the cover 142 to prevent the cover and hence the control member being depressed in the locking position of the control member; the plunger 128 and lug 148 form another of the safety means. When the control member is in the locking position so that the lugs on the harness can be pushed into the box or casing, each lug first comes into contact with the catch 94 moving it to a position in which a projecting portion 100 thereof is clear of the sleeve 80; further movement of the lug into the box or casing pushes the plunger 88 downwardly relative to the sleeve until a hole in the lug is in register with the plunger 88 when the spring 156 urges the plunger upwardly to lock the lug to the box or casing. When the lug is engaged in this manner the catch 94 moves radially outwardly under the influence of the spring 156 and latches over the sleeve 80. In this position gravitational forces cannot cause the plungers to release the lugs since the plungers are locked to the sleeves and the sleeves are restrained from movement by the spider which because of its connection with the control member cannot move. The control member is prevented from axial movement by engagement of the cam-follower 74 with one of the steps in a vertical channel of the control member and also by engagement of the lug 148 on the cover with the plunger 128. Before the lugs are inserted into the box or casing the control member is locked against rotation by the device 104, a spigot 108 of which is in engagement with the notch 64 in the flange of the control member; when the lug is inserted into the box or casing however, its leading end comes into contact with a bevelled face 168 of the device 104 and moves the device upwardly so freeing the spigot from the notch and releasing the control member for rotation when necessary. When the lugs are to be released the cover 142 is turned through approximately 90 degrees, this causes the lug 148 to move clear of the plunger 128 and also because of the rotation of the control member 60 causes the cam-follower 74 to move along the lower series of cam faces from the cam face 116 to the cam face 170; the cover 142 can then be pressed downwardly and this moves the spider 52 downwardly. The spider takes the sleeves with it and since the plungers 88 are locked to the sleeves they also move downwardly to release the lugs. The cam follower moves along one of the vertically-disposed channels into contact with cam face 172 and because of the step in this channel between the cam face 170 and the cam face 172 the control member, plungers and sleeves will remain in the release position. To reset the device to its locking condition the cover 142 is rotated through 90 degrees in the opposite direction to the first-mentioned rotation; when the cover and control member have regained their original positions the cam follower 74 is aligned with the other vertical channel and the springs 156 cause the plungers, sleeves, spider, control member and cover to move upwardly to the locking position. In its rotation the lug 148 comes into contact with the plunger 128 but since the face of the plunger is bevelled the lug causes it to retract, the plunger regaining its normal position when the cover rises vertically.

column12: EXTRUSION OF METAL MATERIAL USING A DUMMY BLOCK HAVING A CURVED SURFACE
column13: Various embodiments provide for an extrusion device with a dummy block having a curved surface configured to change the shape and length of charge welds between extrudates originating from different billets in order to reduce the amount of scrap and waste material. In an embodiment, the dummy block, which forces the billet of material through the die, can have a concave front surface such that the material, as it is extruded through the die, forms a solid-state weld that is shorter than a flat faced dummy block. In another embodiment, the dummy block can have a convex front surface such that the material, as it is extruded through the die, forms a solid-state weld that is longer than a weld due to a flat faced dummy block. In other embodiments, billets with non-flat ends can also be used.

column12: Apparatus and method for rapid transport of an elastic band
column13: An apparatus (21) and method for rapid transport of elastic bands (34) from a band loading station (22) to a band unloading station (23). The apparatus (21) includes a movable arm assembly (24) having a finger (26) thereon dimensioned to loosely receive an elastic band (34) therearound. A drive assembly (36) is coupled to move the arm assembly (24) from the loading (22) to the unloading station (23). The arm assembly (24) is further movable by the drive assembly (36) from a first orientation of the finger (26) to a second orientation of the finger (26) to enable gravity assisted mounting of the band (34) on the finger (26) at the loading station (22) and gravity assisted demounting of the band (34) at the unloading station (23). During the transport of the band (34) between the loading (22) and unloading stations (23), the finger (26) is reoriented along a path maintaining the band (34) on the finger (26) against dynamic forces acting on the band (34) during transport of the arm assembly (24). The apparatus (21) includes a gear train (43, 44, 53, 62) which simultaneously pivots the arm assembly (24) between the loading (22) and unloading station (23) while it rotates the arm (24) in a direction opposed to the pivoting to maintain the band (34) on the finger (26) during pivoting of the arm (24).

column12: Coagulation detection by plunger sensing technique
column13: Coagulation is detected in a fluid sample contained in either a gas flow cartridge or a plunger sensor cartridge, either one of which may be inserted in an actuator mechanism which has the capability of acting on either type of cartridge. Coagulation is detected in the gas flow cartridge by optically sensing the accumulation of coagulating liquid in a foam member at the top of the reaction chamber. In the plunger sensor cartridge, a plunger assembly is raised and released to descend through the sample of liquid in the bottom of the reaction chamber. The plunger assembly descends more slowly upon an increase in the viscosity of the fluid sample due to coagulation. Both cartridges include a lower reagent chamber, an upper reaction chamber, and means initially sealing and thereafter communicating the contents from the reagent chamber to the reaction chamber. The actuator mechanism includes means for delivering the flow of gas to the gas flow cartridge and means for reciprocating the plunger assembly in the plunger sensor cartridge.

column12: Apparatus for coagulation detection by gas flow or plunger sensing techniques
column13: Coagulation is detected in a fluid sample such as blood which has been inserted into a cartridge and operated on by an actuator mechanism. The cartridge may be of either of two types: a plunger sensor cartridge wherein a plunger assembly is reciprocated in a predetermined manner within the fluid sample and the descent of the plunger assembly is sensed to determine coagulation conditions, and a gas flow cartridge wherein gas is passed through the fluid sample to transmit liquid in bubbles and the accumulation of the coagulating liquid from the bubbles is sensed to detect coagulation. An actuator mechanism operates with either one or both types of cartridges to create the conditions under which coagulation can be detected and to sense the coagulation detection conditions. The actuator mechanism reciprocates the plunger assembly and forces gas through the liquid sample to create the bubbles.

column12: SUPERVISORY CIRCUIT FOR PARALLEL CONNECTED DEVICES
column13: SUPERVISORY CIRCUIT FOR PARALLEL CONNECTED DEVICES A supervisory circuit for a plurality of continuously-conductive alarm devices connected in parallel between a pair of conductors monitors the operability of the circuit as well as the operability of each of the devices. Alarm devices having a low impedance are connected between the conductors over a parallel-connected resistor and diode which unidirectionally increases the impedance of such devices. The alarm circuit is connected in one arm of a balanced bridge circuit which has a detecting circuit connected in a further branch of the bridge circuit for monitoring the impedance of the circuit and for providing a supervision signal in response to a change in the impedance of the alarm circuit indicating inoperability of a device or open or short circuit conditions for the conductors which connect the devices into the circuit.

column13: A seal for leaking fissures or faults of a tunnel which has a first, deformable layer with two surfaces, one of which is scalloped in vertical cross-sectional dimension and the other of which abuts a second flexible layer of more dense material such as neoprene. The surface of the second layer remote from the first layer is overlain about its periphery by strapping preferably made from steel. The seals are generally rectangular in horizontal plan and if the seal is sufficiently elongated intermediate strappings are provided between the width end straps as required. column12: Multi-frequency acoustic interrogation for azimuthal orientation of downhole tools
column13: An apparatus for detecting a location of an optical fiber having an acoustic sensor disposed subsurface to the earth includes an acoustic emitter configured to emit a first signal having a first frequency and a second signal having a second frequency that is higher than the first frequency, the first and second emitted acoustic signals being azimuthally rotated around the borehole and an optical interrogator configured to interrogate the optical fiber to receive an acoustic measurement that provides a corresponding first received signal and a corresponding second received signal. The apparatus also includes a processor configured to (i) frequency-multiply the first received signal to provide a third signal having a third frequency within a selected range of the second frequency, (ii) estimate a phase difference between the second received signal and the third signal, and (iii) correlate the phase difference to the location of the optical fiber.

column12: Method for measuring channel characteristics with the internet control message protocol
column13: A method includes constructing a data pattern for generating a reference signal to measure a specific channel characteristic, inserting the data pattern in an Internet Control Message Protocol echo request, transmitting an Internet Control Message Protocol echo request from a primary station across a shared physical medium to a secondary station, receiving the echo request at the secondary station, transmitting an Internet Control Message Protocol echo reply in response to the echo request across the shared physical medium to the primary station, receiving the echo reply at the primary station, measuring a bit slicer error of the Internet Control Message Protocol echo reply, and characterizing the channel quality of the communications channel as a function of the bit slicer error. The corresponding channel quality may be measured for each of a plurality of channels in a multi-channel communications system of an Internet Protocol network and one of the plurality of channels may be selected having the best relative channel quality for routing a communications signal.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR MEASURING THE VIBRATION OF A STRUCTURE
column13: A system and method for measuring the vibration of a structure of interest are disclosed. The disclosure provides an acoustic isolation structure to substantially reduce response to acoustic energy generated by external physical stimuli. The acoustic isolation structure is formed by placing a housing, such as an outer conduit, around an inner conduit, forming a gap between the housing and the inner conduit. The gap is then configured to serve as an acoustic isolation layer by either filling the gap with an acoustic isolation material or by substantially evacuating the gap and sealing the ends thereof.

[Also in Divisions B7 and F2] A release mechanism for a parachute pack comprises an operating device, fastening devices on the parachute pack and a transmission means connecting the operating device with the fastening devices, the operating device being connected to the transmission means through a pulley system so arranged that during the initial movement of the operating device, the operating device moves faster than the'transmission means. In the construction shown the operating device is a handle 11 and the pulley system comprises a casing 22 carrying a carriage 23 (not shown) in which a pulley 17 is freely rotatable and a wire 18 connecting the carriage to the handle. The carriage is freely slidable in the housing and the wire 18 passes round the pulley 17 and the ends of the wire are connected to the handle and to the casing 22 by means of balls 15 and 16 connected to the ends of the wire. The ball 16 is held in a slot in the casing 22 by a breaking tie across the slot. The arrangement provides a mechanical advantage for moving wires 12 and 13 which are connected to the carriage by means of balls 24 and 25 at one end of each and the other end of each being connected to pins 33 which are part of the fastening devices of the parachute pack. Each wire 12 and 13 is covered with a layer of anti-friction material such as PTFE and is contained in a respective sleeve 14; the wire and its covering layer is normally slidable in its sleeve but should the sleeve 14 become damaged so that there is unusual friction between the sleeve and the covering layer then the wire can slide in the covering layer. Each of the fastening devices consists of a conical member 30 provided with a hole 34 to receive the pin 33 and partly protruding into the hole 34 is either a roller, as shown, or a ball to reduce the pull required to withdraw the pin. The operating device instead of being a handle can be a time delay or barometrically operated device.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR MEASURING THE VIBRATION OF A STRUCTURE
column13: A system and method for measuring the vibration of a structure of interest are disclosed. The disclosure provides an acoustic isolation structure to substantially reduce response to acoustic energy generated by external physical stimuli. The acoustic isolation structure is formed by placing a housing, such as an outer conduit, around an inner conduit, forming a gap between the housing and the inner conduit. The gap is then configured to serve as an acoustic isolation layer by either filling the gap with an acoustic isolation material or by substantially evacuating the gap and sealing the ends thereof.

column12: MULTI-FREQUENCY ACOUSTIC INTERROGATION FOR AZIMUTHAL ORIENTATION OF DOWNHOLE TOOLS
column13: An apparatus for detecting a location of an optical fiber having an acoustic sensor disposed subsurface to the earth includes an acoustic emitter configured to emit a first signal having a first frequency and a second signal having a second frequency that is higher than the first frequency, the first and second emitted acoustic signals being azimuthally rotated around the borehole and an optical interrogator configured to interrogate the optical fiber to receive an acoustic measurement that provides a corresponding first received signal and a corresponding second received signal. The apparatus also includes a processor configured to (i) frequency-multiply the first received signal to provide a third signal having a third frequency within a selected range of the second frequency, (ii) estimate a phase difference between the second received signal and the third signal, and (iii) correlate the phase difference to the location of the optical fiber.

column12: Method for measuring channel characteristics with the internet control message protocol
column13: A method includes constructing a data pattern for generating a reference signal to measure a specific channel characteristic, inserting the data pattern in an Internet Control Message Protocol echo request, transmitting an Internet Control Message Protocol echo request from a primary station across a shared physical medium to a secondary station, receiving the echo request at the secondary station, transmitting an Internet Control Message Protocol echo reply in response to the echo request across the shared physical medium to the primary station, receiving the echo reply at the primary station, measuring a bit slicer error of the Internet Control Message Protocol echo reply, and characterizing the channel quality of the communications channel as a function of the bit slicer error. The corresponding channel quality may be measured for each of a plurality of channels in a multi-channel communications system of an Internet Protocol network and one of the plurality of channels may be selected having the best relative channel quality for routing a communications signal.

column12: Intrinsic viscosity control of polyphenylene ether reaction mixtures
column13: Polyphenylene ethers produced by an oxidative coupling of a phenol in the presence of an oxygen-containing gas and a metal-amine complex catalyst are freed of catalyst and stabilized against molecular weight loss. Removal of the metal component and molecular weight loss control are effected by contacting the reaction mixture with an aromatic amine plus a metal chelating agent, which stabilizes the intrinsic viscosity of the polyphenylene ether in the reaction mixture. This procedure results in lower catalyst usage and shorter reaction time.

column12: Interrogación acústica de multifrecuencia para la orientación acimutal de herramientas de fondo de pozo

column12: PROCEDE DE FABRICATION DE POLY(OXYPHENYLENE) PAR COUPLAGE OXYDANT EN PRESENCE D'UN CATALYSEUR COMPLEXE
column13:
Procédé permettant une élimination facile et économique des résidus de catalyseur métallique.

Il consiste à faire passer un gaz renfermant de l'oxygène à travers une solution réactionnelle d'un phénol et du catalyseur, à terminer la réaction et à stabiliser le polymère contre une dégradation par mise en contact de la solution réactionnelle avec i un agent de chélation de l'ion en combinaison avec ii un diphénol et un agent réducteur et à récupérer le poly(oxyphénylène) de la solution réactionnelle.

Application à la fabrication du poly(oxydiméthyl-2,6 phénylène-1,4).

column12: System and Methods of Language Processing
column13: The disclosure relates to the field of language processing. A server ( 30 ) is configured to respond to a query associated with a user device ( 21 ) by sending, to the user device ( 21 ), an indication of an item selected based on semantic importance attributed to grams of text in the query. Attributing semantic importance comprises: in the event that a number of occurrences of the gram in a first document is above an occurrence threshold, determining a gram score for said gram based on said number of occurrences; in the event that the number of occurrences of the gram in the first document is below the occurrence threshold, determining the gram score based on: (i) said number of occurrences, and (ii) a reference score for the gram based on a number of occurrences of the gram in a reference document different to the at least one first document; and attributing the semantic importance based on the gram score.

column12: Supervisory circuit for parallel connected devices
column13: A supervisory circuit for a plurality of continuously-conductive alarm devices connected in parallel between a pair of conductors monitors the operability of the circuit as well as the operability of each of the devices. Alarm devices having a low impedance are connected between the conductors over a parallel-connected resistor and diode which unidirectionally increases the impedance of such devices. The alarm circuit is connected in one arm of a balanced bridge circuit which has a detecting circuit connected in a further branch of the bridge circuit for monitoring the impedance of the circuit and for providing a supervision signal in response to a change in the impedance of the alarm circuit indicating inoperability of a device or open or short circuit conditions for the conductors which connect the devices into the circuit.

column12: Molecular weight control of polyphenylene ethers
column13: Polyphenylene ethers produced by an oxidative coupling of a phenol in the presence of an oxygen-containing gas and a metal-amine complex catalyst are freed of catalyst and stabilized against molecular weight loss. Removal of the metal component and molecular weight loss control are effected by contacting the solution with a compound capable of selectively complexing with the metal in combination with a dihydric phenol and a mild reducing agent. The process is less expensive than prior art procedures because less dihydric phenol is needed, and the metallic residue content of the polyphenylene ether is reduced to very low levels.

column12: USING THE STATE OF A REQUEST ROUTING MECHANISM TO INFORM ATTACK DETECTION AND MITIGATION
column13: Among other things, this document describes systems, methods and apparatus for identifying and mitigating network attacks, particularly botnet attacks and other volumetric attacks. In some embodiments, a distributed computing platform provides client-facing service endpoints and a request routing mechanism (request router or RR) directing clients to a particular service endpoint or cluster thereof to obtain a service. The state of the RR at a given time is communicated to enforcement points in the system, which may be cluster equipment, service endpoints, or other components. When client traffic arrives at a particular enforcement point it is checked for consistency with the RR's directions, referred to as 'mapping consistency'. This information is incorporated into decisions about how to handle the packets from the client.

column12: Low-Fat Table Spread and process for preparing the same
column13: 1,187,232. Low fat table spread. CORN PRODUCTS CO. 30 Aug., 1967, No. 39764/67. Heading C5C. A low-fat table spread comprises 55-65% of an aqueous phase dispersed in 45-35% of a fat, the aqueous phase being substantially free of protein and the fat phase providing the solid fat to make the spread a solid at about 70‹ F. If the spread is in print form the fat phase has the following solid content index values: 15-25 at 50‹ F.; 8À5-15À5 at 70‹ F., 5-10À5 at 80‹ F. and 0-3À5 at 92‹ F. If the spread is packed in a tub the corresponding S.C.I. values for the fat phase are 8-15; 5-8À5; 2À5-5; and 0-1À5. In the examples the base oils are corn, safflower, soybean, cottonseed oils and partially hydrogenated forms of these oils. Additives which may be present are salt, EDTA and potassium sorbate in the aq. phase and Vitamins A and D isopropyl citrate, mono- and di-glycerides and lecithin in the oil phase.

column12: Gas flow cartridge having resilient flexible membrane with slit separating reaction and reagent chambers
column13: A gas flow cartridge in which to conduct analytical coagulation tests on a sample of fluid such as blood includes a tube-like member and a resilient flexible membrane having a slit formed therethrough to divide the tube-like member into an upper reaction chamber in which the test takes place and into a lower reagent chamber which initially contains reagent to be mixed with the sample of liquid upon which the test is to be conducted. The contents of the reagent chamber are forced through the slit in the resilient flexible membrane due to the flexing of the membrane around the slit when pressure is applied. column12: Synchronized multiple image tomographic cardiography
column13: A scan converter storage surface is divided into image spaces corresponding to different points in the heart cycle. Ultrasound echoes from heart structures are plotted in the image spaces by means of special x, y sweeps which are offset to the image spaces by timing circuitry. Separate delay and spacing counters allow the first image to be stored at one interval after detection of the ECG R-wave and successive images to be stored at a another uniform interval. An ECG trace is stored in the first image space with cursors indicating the selected image timing. The scan converter is read out to a TV display. During image build-up, the read and write modes alternate. If desired, the TV sweeps to the scan converter may be attenuated and offset to display a single stored image. Images displayed in sequence provide animation. A self test circuit substitutes a fake ECG and writes bars in the scan converter image spaces using TV sweeps for the scan sweeps. The timing circuitry for the normal images gates the video for the bars. All of the timing for the system is derived from a TV composite sync signal and the patient's ECG current.

column12: System and method for controlling operations of a vehicle consist based on location data
column13: Systems and methods are described for monitoring different conditions that are simultaneously or concurrently experienced by different vehicles in the same consist and using the monitored conditions to locally change operations of one or more of the vehicles. Command data is formed based on the operations data and the location data. The command data directs at least one of the vehicles in the consist to change one or more operations of the at least one of the vehicles. column13: Methods, systems, and media for dynamically detecting mobile environment information are provided. In some implementations, a method for detecting mobile environment information for advertisement requests, the method comprising: receiving a request for advertising content from an advertisement tag; applying one or more JavaScript objects to return a URL of an advertisement web view, wherein the advertisement website is generated by an advertisement software development kit to contain an advertisement responsive to the request; extracting keywords from the URL of the advertisement web view; determining whether the advertisement tag is running within a mobile application based on a comparison of the extracted keywords with known mobile application information; in response to determining that the advertisement tag is running within the mobile application, determining the advertisement software development kit from a plurality of advertisement software development kits that the advertisement tag is running in by: applying a plurality of JavaScript objects that are made available by the advertisement software development kit to return properties of the advertisement software development kit; and comparing the returned properties with a database of known software development kit information; and transmitting an indication that associates the advertisement software development kit used within a mobile application environment with the advertisement tag.

column12: System and methods of language processing
column13: The disclosure relates to the field of language processing. A server ( 30 ) is configured to respond to a query associated with a user device ( 21 ) by sending, to the user device ( 21 ), an indication of an item selected based on semantic importance attributed to grams of text in the query. Attributing semantic importance comprises: in the event that a number of occurrences of the gram in a first document is above an occurrence threshold, determining a gram score for said gram based on said number of occurrences; in the event that the number of occurrences of the gram in the first document is below the occurrence threshold, determining the gram score based on: (i) said number of occurrences, and (ii) a reference score for the gram based on a number of occurrences of the gram in a reference document different to the at least one first document; and attributing the semantic importance based on the gram score.

column12: Reaction products of polyesters with polyisocyanates or polyisothiocyanates
column13: A process for the preparation of a stable reaction product of a polyester with a polyisocyanate or polyisothiocyanate comprises mixing with the reaction product within a short time of preparation thereof an oxyacid of phosphorus in an amount sufficient to retard cross-linking thereof. Suitable acids are orthophosphoric, metaphosphoric, pyrophosphoric, phosphorous and hypophosphorous acids. The amount is preferably 0.02 to 0.5% by weight of the reaction product. The acids may be used in conjunction with cyclic or acyclic acid chlorides, acid esters of phosphorus-containing acids and/or nitro derivatives of aromatic sulphenyl halides, for example, mixtures of orthophosphoric acid a p-nitrobenzoyl chloride; phosphorous acid and fumaryl chloride; pyrophosphoric acid and butyl hydrogen phosphate; orthophosphoric acid and ortho-nitrobenzenesulphenyl chloride. Preferably reaction products of linear polyesters are employed and there may also be used cross-linking agents such as water, polyvalent alcohols, polyvalent amines, e.g. o,o1-dichlorobenzidine or p-phenylenediamine, guanidine or amino-alcohols. Before moulding the acid in the compositions is neutralized, by incorporating (by milling) either an excess of cross-linking agent (when this is of a basic character) or such materials as diphenylamine, para-phenylenediamine, diphenylguanidine, guanidine, aniline, benzidine, o,o - dichlorobenzidine, anisidine, amino-pyridine, 2 - 2 - dipyridylamine, 2 - amino - 4 : 6 - dimethylpyridine, hexamethylene tetramine, hydrazine hydrate, magnesium oxide, calcium hydroxide and ammonium carbonate. Additional polyisocyanate to bring the ratio of polyester from 1:1.01 to 1:1.10 up to between 1:1.4 and 1:1.6 may be milled in at the same time. Carbon black, silica or other fillers can also be incorporated. Specifications 790,543, 791,956 and 831,302 are referred to.

column12: System and Methods of Language Processing
column13: The disclosure related to the field of language processing. A server ( 30 ) is configured to respond to a query associated with a user device ( 21 ) by sending, to the user device ( 21 ), an indication of an item selected based on semantic importance attributed to grams of text in the query. Attributing semantic importance comprises: in the event that a number of occurrences of the gram in a first document is above an occurrence threshold, determining a gram score for said gram based on said number of occurrences; in the vent that the number of occurrences of the gram in the first document is below the occurrence threshold, determining the gram score based on: (i) said number of occurrences, and (ii) a reference score for the gram based on a number of occurrences of the gram in a reference document different to the at least one first document; and attributing the semantic importance based on the gram score.

column12: Methods, systems, and media for dynamically detecting mobile environment information
column13: Methods, systems, and media for dynamically detecting mobile environment information are provided. In some implementations, a method for detecting mobile environment information for advertisement requests, the method comprising: receiving a request for advertising content from an advertisement tag; applying one or more JavaScript objects to return a URL of an advertisement web view, wherein the advertisement website is generated by an advertisement software development kit to contain an advertisement responsive to the request; extracting keywords from the URL of the advertisement web view; determining whether the advertisement tag is running within a mobile application based on a comparison of the extracted keywords with known mobile application information; in response to determining that the advertisement tag is running within the mobile application, determining the advertisement software development kit from a plurality of advertisement software development kits that the advertisement tag is running in by: applying a plurality of JavaScript objects that are made available by the advertisement software development kit to return properties of the advertisement software development kit; and comparing the returned properties with a database of known software development kit information; and transmitting an indication that associates the advertisement software development kit used within a mobile application environment with the advertisement tag.

column12: Device-under-test power management
column13: One embodiment of the present invention includes a system for managing power to a plurality of devices-under-test (DUTs). The system comprises a DUT test system configured to perform at least one test associated with operation of the DUTs and to monitor current associated the at least one test of the plurality of DUTs. The DUT test system can communicate an instruction to a subset of the plurality of DUTs to cancel the at least one test if the monitored current is greater than a predetermined threshold. Each of the plurality of DUTs can comprise restart logic configured to restart the at least one test of the subset of the plurality of DUTs after being cancelled in response to the instruction.

column12: Gas flow coagulation test cartridge having movable member establishing communication between reagent and reaction chambers
column13: A gas flow cartridge in which to conduct a coagulation-related test uses an elongated pin member movably positioned within a communication opening which separates a reagent chamber from a reaction chamber. A first portion of the pin member has an operative configuration for sealing the communication opening when the first portion is positioned in the communication opening. A second longitudinally displaced portion of the pin member opens the communication opening to further communication therethrough upon longitudinal movement of the pin member. At the commencement of an analytical test, a plug member is moved upwardly to contact the pin member and move the first portion out of the communication opening and the second portion into the communication opening. The upward movement of the lower plug member forces the contents of the reagent chamber through the opened communication opening and into the reaction chamber. A pointed needle-like member pierces a membrane of the lower plug member and injects gas into the cartridge. The gas also flows through the opened communication opening.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR CONTROLLING OPERATIONS OF A VEHICLE CONSIST BASED ON LOCATION DATA
column13: Systems and methods are described for monitoring different conditions that are simultaneously or concurrently experienced by different vehicles in the same consist and using the monitored conditions to locally change operations of one or more of the vehicles. In accordance with one embodiment, operations data related to one or more vehicles of the consist is acquired from one or more of plural different locations in the consist. The operations data and location data related to where the operations data is acquired are communicated to a first vehicle of the consist. Command data is formed based on the operations data and the location data. The command data directs at least one of the vehicles in the consist to change one or more operations of the at least one of the vehicles. The command data is transmitted to one or more of the vehicles of the consist.

column12: BEAM STEERING FOR LASER RADAR AND OTHER USES
column13: Optical systems suitable for use as or in laser radar systems and other uses include a beam-forming unit, a beam-scan unit, and a controller. The beam-forming unit includes a first optical element, and the beam-scan unit includes a second optical element. The first optical element is movable to shape and direct a substantially collimated optical beam along a nominal propagation axis to a target, and the second optical element includes at least one movable beam deflector that moves the optical beam in a scanning manner relative to the nominal propagation axis. The controller is coupled to the beam-forming unit and beam-scan unit, and is configured to induce movement of the first optical element required for shaping and directing the optical beam along the nominal propagation axis and to induce independent motion of the beam deflector of the second optical element as required to scan the optical beam relative to the nominal propagation axis. The beam deflector can be refractive or reflective.

column12: PERSONAL CARE COMPOSITIONS
column13: Personal care compositions comprise: a) from 4 to 12 parts by weight of a dibenzoylmethane sunscreening compound; b) from 3 to 9 parts by weight of a cyano-diphenyl acrylate sunscreening compound; c) from 2.5 to 7.5 parts by weight of a salicylate sunscreening compound; and d) from 0.5 to 1.5 parts by weight of a triazinic sunscreening compound. The personal care compositions exhibit relatively uniform absorption across the whole of the UVA and UVB spectral range. The compositions may provide higher SPF's than those achieved with the individual sunscreening compounds alone.

column12: Methods, systems, and media for dynamically detecting mobile environment information
column13: Methods, systems, and media for dynamically detecting mobile environment information are provided. In some implementations, a method for detecting mobile environment information for advertisement requests, the method comprising: receiving a request for advertising content from an advertisement tag; applying one or more JavaScript objects to return a URL of an advertisement web view, wherein the advertisement website is generated by an advertisement software development kit to contain an advertisement responsive to the request; extracting keywords from the URL of the advertisement web view; determining whether the advertisement tag is running within a mobile application based on a comparison of the extracted keywords with known mobile application information; in response to determining that the advertisement tag is running within the mobile application, determining the advertisement software development kit from a plurality of advertisement software development kits that the advertisement tag is running in by: applying a plurality of JavaScript objects that are made available by the advertisement software development kit to return properties of the advertisement software development kit; and comparing the returned properties with a database of known software development kit information; and transmitting an indication that associates the advertisement software development kit used within a mobile application environment with the advertisement tag.

column12: Load control device for controlling a driver for a lighting load
column13: A load control device is configured to generate a control signal having a desired magnitude for controlling a load regulation device adapted to control the power delivered to an electrical load. The load control device may comprise a control terminal arranged to provide the control signal to the load regulation device, a communication circuit for generating the control signal, and a control circuit configured to generate an output signal that is provided to the communication circuit. The communication circuit may be characterized by non-linear operation. The control circuit may adjust the magnitude of the output signal in response to the difference between the magnitude of the control signal and the desired magnitude to adjust the magnitude of the control signal towards the desired magnitude. The control circuit may also be configured to determine if an incompatible load regulation device is coupled to the load control device.

column12: Method and apparatus for creating and delivering an atomic remote control macro
column13: A method in a signaling device for delivering codes to control multimedia devices. In response to receiving a signal from a remote control device, a macro corresponding to the signal is identified, the identified macro contains a set of codes used to control a set of multimedia devices. The set of codes is transmitted, wherein the set of codes causes a series of events to occur in the set of multimedia devices.

column12: Fuzzy logic expert system for an implantable cardiac device
column13: A diagnostic device makes use of knowledge based rule system for making a prognosis of a cardiac malfunction based on operation parameters and/or patient characteristics received from a cardiac implant. The device generates a symptoms vector from the information received from the implant, and using the expert rules to generate an appropriate prognosis. Both pathological problems and programming problems may be detected in this manner.

column12: PROSTATE CANCER MARKERS
column13: A method of predicting a patient's prognosis of prostate cancer, the method comprising providing and analysing a patients germline genetic material and detecting germline variants of genes up-regulated by activation of the PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway, genes up-regulated by activation of the PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway, genes up-regulated by KRAS activation, genes up-regulated in response to low oxygen levels, genes regulated by NF-kB in response to tumour necrosis factor (TNF) and/or genes specifically up-regulated in pancreatic beta cells or at least one gene from Table 1. Also provided is a method of determining treatment regimen and a biomarker panel.

column12: LOAD CONTROL DEVICE FOR CONTROLLING A DRIVER FOR A LIGHTING LOAD.
column13: A load control device (200) is configured to generate a control signal (Vcs) having a desired magnitude for controlling a load regulation device (204) adapted to control the power delivered to an electrical load (206). The load control device (200) may comprise a control terminal arranged to provide the control signal (Vcs) to the load regulation device (204), a communication circuit (230) for generating the control signal (Vcs), and a control circuit (210) configured to generate an output signal (Vdc) that is provided to the communication circuit (230). The communication circuit (230) may be characterized by non-linear operation. The control circuit (210) may adjust the magnitude of the output signal (Vdc) in response to the difference between the magnitude of the control signal (Vcs) and the desired magnitude to adjust the magnitude of the control signal (Vcs) towards the desired magnitude. The control circuit (210) may also be configured to determine if an incompatible load regulation device is coupled to the load control device (200).

column12: METHOD OF DETECTING AND CONTROLLING E-LINE LOSS
column13: A method of detecting E-line loss in a disc stack centrifuge is provided, comprising: collecting data from at least one instrument associated with the centrifuge over a specific time period; calculating one or more indicators by comparing the collected data with expected values from a normally operating centrifuge, the indicators being indicative of a start of an E-line loss event; calculating the probability of E-line loss by applying weighted voting to the indicators to yield a probability value; and activating an alert upon determination that the probability value exceeds a threshold value.

column12: NAVIGABLE LAYERING OF VIEWABLE AREAS FOR HIERARCHICAL CONTENT
column13: Exemplary embodiments are generally directed to navigable layering of viewable areas corresponding to a hierarchical structure of computer-readable content. In exemplary embodiments, a stack of viewable areas including a first viewable area and a second viewable area can be rendered on a display within a footprint area. An order of the viewable areas in the stack can correspond to a hierarchical relationship of computer-readable content and the viewable areas can include information associated with the hierarchical relationship. The second viewable area in the stack can be adjusted, for example, by resizing and/or repositioning the second viewable area, based on a compression criteria to accommodate the viewable areas of the stack within the footprint.

column12: Method and system for maintaining client cache coherency in a distributed network system
column13: A distributed network system includes a distributed server system and a plurality of client devices that are communicatively coupled to the distributed server system. The distributed server system includes multiple servers, each server including a set of client devices registered with the server. Through client re-registration, a client device can move its registration from one server to another server. Through server-side data replication, an object registration request submitted by a client device to a first server is forwarded to a second server without having the client device submitting the same request to the second server.

The communication circuit (230) may be characterized by non-linear operation. The control circuit (210) may adjust the magnitude of the output signal (Vdc) in response to the difference between the magnitude of the control signal (Vcs) and the desired magnitude to adjust the magnitude of the control signal (Vcs) towards the desired magnitude. column12: RECURSIVE NOISE REDUCTION FILTER FOR VIDEO COMPONENTS
column13: A recursive noise reduction filter for video components reduces the noise bandwidth of a signal without degrading the signal spectrum. Demodulated chrominance or peak detected chrominance from a video signal output by a video system in response to a video test signal is input to the recursive noise reduction filter (24) which acts as a comb filter to suppress noise significantly at frequencies other than harmonics of the horizontal line rate. The signal is scaled by a first attenuator (30) having a scaling factor of (1-a), where (a) is less than one, and input to a summing circuit (32). Also input to the summing circuit is a delayed signal from a prior horizontal line scaled by the scaling factor (a). The output of the summing circuit is a filtered output signal. The signal is sampled only during horizontal lines that have the video test signal and is stored for subsequent accumulation with other horizontal lines also having the video test signal. The filter serves to add the vertically correlated part of the signal corresponding to the video test signal while averaging out the noise, thus improving the overall signal to noise ratio without degrading the signal spectrum and, hence, enhancing differential gain and phase measurements.

column13: A downhole tool orientation determination system to determine a radial orientation of a tool conveyed downhole into a pipe via a carrier and a method of determining a radial orientation of a tool conveyed downhole into a pipe via a carrier are described. The system includes an orientation tool conveyed downhole by the carrier that conveys the tool, and a distributed acoustic sensor (DAS). The DAS includes an optical fiber disposed axially along an outer surface of the pipe; and a processor to determine an orientation of the orientation tool with respect to the optical fiber based on a measurement by the optical fiber at different rotational positions of the orientation tool. The processor determines the radial orientation of the tool with respect to the optical fiber based on the orientation of the orientation tool with respect to the optical fiber.

column12: USING THE STATE OF A REQUEST ROUTING MECHANISM TO INFORM ATTACK DETECTION AND MITIGATION
column13: Among other things, this document describes systems, methods and apparatus for identifying and mitigating network attacks, particularly botnet attacks and other volumetric attacks. In some embodiments, a distributed computing platform provides client-facing service endpoints and a request routing mechanism (request router or RR) directing clients to a particular service endpoint or cluster thereof to obtain a service. The state of the RR at a given time is communicated to enforcement points in the system, which may be cluster equipment, service endpoints, or other components. When client traffic arrives at a particular enforcement point it is checked for consistency with the RR's directions, referred to as ‘mapping consistency’. This information is incorporated into decisions about how to handle the packets from the client.

column12: CONVEYOR SYSTEM FOR VISCOUS OR CEMENTITIOUS MATERIAL
column13: An adaptable, flexible conveyor system is provided which employs material carrying continuous belt pick-up, conveyor-transfer and turret sections. The conveyor sections are at their adjacent ends positioned in a forwardly and backwardly movably supported and horizontally-pivoted relation with respect to each other and with respect to a pick-up and to a turret section from whose continuous conveyor, cementitious, grout or somewhat viscous material is delivered to a work area. The turret section and the head end of a transfer section with which it cooperates to receive material therefrom are both mounted for forward and backward movement on a longitudinally-extending elevated track. A transfer assembly is pivotally-carried between the forward end of one conveyor section and the tail end of a cooperating conveyor section to which the material is to be delivered, and a scraper assembly is carried by the forward end of the one conveyor section within the transfer assembly for removing adhering material from the belt adjacent a head pulley. A combination scraper means is provided for cleaning an underside of a belt and the exposed side of a drive pulley at the tail end of each conveyor section which has its own individual drive unit that is mounted to facilitate adjustment of belt tension and replacement of the belt.

column12: MEMORY BUFFER FOR VECTOR STREAMING
column13: 1278101 Digital data processor TEXAS INSTRUMENTS Inc 12 June 1969 [11 July 1968] 29853/69 Heading G4A The invention relates to a computer performing arithmetic operations on vectors. A computer has a central processing unit, a peripheral processing unit containing a plurality of virtual processors coupled to a common arithmetic unit, several memory units including magnetic tape, disc and thin film, a card reader and punch, a line printer, cathode ray tubes and keyboards. The CPU 10 executes user programs which require input/output services from the PPU 11. Programs which can proceed without waiting for an I/O service to be provided request a system call and proceed SCP command on line 41 and the program continues. Programs which cannot proceed without the service wait and a new program is selected. The PPU constantly analyses the programs in CPU 10 not being executed and chooses which is to be executed next and sets a switch plug 44. When a SCW command appears from the CPU on line 42 the switch plug enables an AND gate 43 which resets the plug and causes an indication of the next program to be executed to be fed to the CPU. This enables the next program to be executed without delay caused by a dialogue between the CPU and the PPU. The computer opsrates on vectors (X 1 , X 2 ... X n ) and is arranged to multiply matrices where To produce the matrix C two program loops are followed, an inner loop to produce rows e.g. C 11 ,C 12 ,C 13 and an outer loop changing the indices to allow the inner loop to produce the next row. The computer communicates at high speed with the arithmetic unit and is capable of looking at four succeeding operations at the same time (Fig. 7) so that as the arithmetic unit is performing a calculation T 1 Store/Fetch and Control Units are preparing for the next operation T 2 , the index and instruction buffer units prepare for the following operation T 3 and the instruction Fetch Unit is obtaining the next instruction. Data to the AU is passed via buffers A<SP>1</SP>, A and B<SP>1</SP>, B and is returned via buffers C<SP>1</SP>, C a word being supplied per clock pulse and an arithmetical operation being performed in general during a clock pulse. A generic vector instruction acquired in Unit 128 transfers data from a vector parameter file 125 to file 132 so that complex vector operations are specified at the machine language level. The file 132, used for multiplying vectors A and B to produce C, defines the starting addresses in store of the three vectors, the number of elements in the operation, the number of turns in each loop and the address increments for each loop and the file works in conjunction with file 133 holding the current address of the vectors and the vector and loop counts. The arithmetic unit is pipe-lined and has several units performing different jobs and capable of being cross coupled in different ways. The virtual processors are selected by means of the unit shown in Fig. 13. As described, 8 virtual processors are used and two registers between them holding as many four bit words as there are time sharing slots in a timing cycle are provided, each four bit word feeding a set of four AND gates, which sets are successively enabled by a counter 418 fed with clock pulses. Each AND gate of a set feeds a separate OR gate 450-453 which feeds a register coupled to a decoder 455. Each four bit word contains 3 bits identifying one of the eight processors and one bit enabling or inhibiting the decoder. The decoder supplies a signal coupling one of the processors and the arithmetic unit together. column12: Process for sweetening liquid hydrocarbons
column13: A process for sweetening high mercaptan content gasoline or other liquid hydrocarbons is disclosed which utilizes aqueous caustic solution. A recycle stream is used to increase the conversion potential by reducing the relative mercaptan concentration of the untreated gasoline. Part of the treated gasoline effluent is recycled to the untreated feed. The treated gasoline has a low mercaptan concentration while the untreated gasoline is high in mercaptans. As the two streams combine, the feed to the unit becomes less concentrated in mercaptan compounds. In effect, the mercaptan concentration of the untreated gasoline has been diluted by the treated gasoline. Nitrogen inhibits the solubility of oxygen into gasoline. Nitrogen present in the recycle stream would create a system high in nitrogen and low in oxygen. By increasing the level of nitrogen, oxygen is limited in its ability to complete the sweetening reaction. In order to keep nitrogen from inhibiting oxygen, the gasoline effluent is sent to a low pressure separation vessel. in this vessel, nitrogen gas separates from the liquid gasoline. Part of this liquid gasoline stream is recycled to join with the untreated gasoline. The recycle gasoline is now free of nitrogen that would inhibit the solubility of oxygen.
